The paper proposes an energy-efficient approach for performing vector-by-matrix multiplication in a time domain, which is relevant to several sub-fields of computer science. The use of current sources and subthreshold regime suggests a focus on analog and mixed-signal circuits, which is reflected in the cs.ET (Emerging Technologies) category. The application of the approach to multilayer perceptrons and neurocomputing suggests a focus on artificial intelligence and machine learning, which is reflected in the cs.AR (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) categories. The paper also discusses drain-induced barrier lowering and memory cell measurements, which suggest a focus on circuit design and device modeling, which is reflected in the cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science) and cs.DC (Digital Circuits) categories.
